    <h1 class="heading">Fonts with Google Fonts</h1>
    
    <p class="info">
          <strong>Google Fonts</strong> allows you to pick from a variety of cool looking fonts to make your site look cleaner, more professional, or more crazy if that’s the look you’re going for. To be able to use Google Fonts, we’re going to have to <code>&lt;link&gt;</code> it in our <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> element. This is similar to how we have been linking our other external CSS and similar to how we linked Bootstrap in the other section. But before we link, we must pick out what fonts we want to use.
          <br><br>
    </p>
    
    <div class="container">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col">
          <p class="info" style="padding:20px;">
          Browse Google Fonts and find what font(s) you're interested in.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <div style="padding:20px;">
            <a class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" style="padding:10px;" href="https://fonts.google.com/" target="_blank">
            Link to Google Fonts
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <img src="/images/gfonts1.jpeg" alt="Google Fonts 1" style="width:700px;height:400px;" class="center"><br><br>
    
    <p class="info">
      Once you’ve decided that you’re into it, click on the red plus button in the top right hand corner of each font. You can continue adding more and more fonts that you’re interested in. There’s no limit to how many you add at a time. Google Fonts will generate the <code>&lt;link&gt;</code> that you need to include in your <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> of the HTML file you want these fonts to apply to.
      <br><br>
    </p>
    <img src="/images/gfonts2.jpeg" alt="Google Fonts 2" style="width:700px;height:400px;" class="center"><br><br>
    <p class="info">
      In the photo above, you can see that Google Fonts has supplied you the correct <code>&lt;link&gt;</code> to add to the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> of your HTML file, and how to use that font in your CSS file (under “Specify in CSS”). Just make sure to include it in the stylings of the text that you want it to apply to; the possibilities are endless! Good luck!
      <br><br>
    </p>
    
